{"title_page": "La Provence", "text_new": "{{other uses|Provence (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name =La Provence\n| image = \n| type = [[Daily newspaper]]\n| format = [[Berliner (format)|Berliner]]\n| foundation = 1997\n| owners = Groupe Bernard Tapie \n| publisher = [[Hachette Filipacchi Medias]]\n| language = [[French language|French]]\n| headquarters = \n| editor = Hedi Dahmani\n| website = [http://www.laprovence.com/ www.laprovence.com]\n}}\n\n'''''La Provence''''' is a French language [[daily newspaper]] published in [[Marseille]], France.\n\n==History and profile==\nIn 1997 ''La Provence'' was created in Marseille from the merger of two daily newspapers, ''[[Le Proven\u00e7al]]'' of former Interior Minister [[Gaston Defferre]] and the ''[[Le M\u00e9ridional]]'' of shipowner and congressman, [[Jean Alfred Fraissinet]].\n\n''La Provence'' was jointly owned by the [[Hersant|Groupe Hersant M\u00e9dia]] and the Groupe Bernard Tapie until July 2013 when the latter became the sole owner of the paper.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bernard Tapie becomes sole shareholder of La Provence after split with Hersant family|url=http://blog.wan-ifra.org/2013/07/29/bernard-tapie-becomes-sole-shareholder-of-la-provence-after-split-with-hersant-family|accessdate=24 February 2015|work=WAN IFRA|date=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Reporters Without Borders accuse businessman Bernard Tapie|url=http://mediafreedom.ushahidi.com/reports/view/107|accessdate=24 February 2015|work=Reporters without Borders|date=10 March 2014}}</ref> The publisher of the paper is [[Hachette Filipacchi Medias]], a subsidiary of [[Lagard\u00e8re Publishing|Lagard\u00e8re]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Hartmut Walravens|title=International Newspaper Librarianship for the 21st Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g3-LvEMFlYkC&pg=PA101|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-598-44020-5|page=101}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|France|Journalism}}\n* [[List of newspapers in France]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.laprovence.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Newspapers in France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Provence}}\n[[Category:1997 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n[[Category:Media in Marseille]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Provence (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name =La Provence\n| image = \n| type = [[Daily newspaper]]\n| format = [[Berliner (format)|Berliner]]\n| foundation = 1997\n| owners = Groupe Bernard Tapie \n| publisher = [[Hachette Filipacchi Medias]]\n| language = [[French language|French]]\n| headquarters = \n| editor = Hedi Dahmani\n| website = [http://www.laprovence.com/ www.laprovence.com]\n}}\n\n'''''La Provence''''' is a French language [[daily newspaper]] published in [[Marseille]], France.\n\n==History and profile==\nIn 1997 ''La Provence'' was created in Marseille from the merger of two daily newspapers, ''[[Le Proven\u00e7al]]'' of former Interior Minister [[Gaston Defferre]] and the ''[[Le M\u00e9ridional]]'' of shipowner and congressman, [[Jean Alfred Fraissinet]].\n\n''La Provence'' was jointly owned by the [[Hersant|Groupe Hersant M\u00e9dia]] and the Groupe Bernard Tapie until July 2013 when the latter became the sole owner of the paper.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bernard Tapie becomes sole shareholder of La Provence after split with Hersant family|url=http://blog.wan-ifra.org/2013/07/29/bernard-tapie-becomes-sole-shareholder-of-la-provence-after-split-with-hersant-family|accessdate=24 February 2015|work=WAN IFRA|date=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Reporters Without Borders accuse businessman Bernard Tapie|url=http://mediafreedom.ushahidi.com/reports/view/107|accessdate=24 February 2015|work=Reporters without Borders|date=10 March 2014}}</ref> The publisher of the paper is [[Hachette Filipacchi Medias]], a subsidiary of [[Lagard\u00e8re Publishing|Lagard\u00e8re]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Hartmut Walravens|title=International Newspaper Librarianship for the 21st Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g3-LvEMFlYkC&pg=PA101|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-598-44020-5|page=101}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|France|Journalism}}\n* [[List of newspapers in France]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.laprovence.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Newspapers in France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Provence}}\n[[Category:1997 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in France]]\n[[Category:Media in Marseille]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Provence"}
{"title_page": "Le Progr\u00e8s", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                = Le Progr\u00e8s\n| image               = Le Progr\u00e8s newspaper nameplate.jpg\n| caption             = \n| type                = [[Daily newspaper]]\n| format              = [[Broadsheet]]\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|1859}} \n| ceased publication  = \n| price               = \n| owners              = L'est R\u00e9publicain\n| political position  = \n| publisher           = \n| editor              = \n| language       = [[French language|French]]\n| circulation         = \n| headquarters        = [[Lyon]]\n| ISSN                = \n| website             = [http://www.leprogres.fr ''Le Progr\u00e8s'']\n}}\n\n'''''Le Progr\u00e8s''''' is a regional daily newspaper which is based in [[Lyon]], [[Rh\u00f4ne (department)|Rh\u00f4ne]].<ref name=\"KiddReynolds2014\">{{cite book|author1=William Kidd|author2=Sian Reynolds|title=Contemporary French Cultural Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=45h9AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA235|accessdate=22 November 2014|date=1 May 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-4441-6556-2|page=235}}</ref>\n\n''Le Progr\u00e8s'' reports primarily on local news in the [[Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]] region. The paper has its headquarters in Lyon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Newspapers: First in a Series on the French Media|url=http://www.wikileaks.ch/cable/2006/11/06PARIS7251.html|work=Wikileaks|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=6 November 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207141142/http://www.wikileaks.ch/cable/2006/11/06PARIS7251.html|archivedate=7 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The print works is in [[Chassieu]], near Lyon. The former headquarters was located in the [[Rue de la R\u00e9publique]], in the building that is currently occupied by [[Fnac]]. [[Ren\u00e9 Diaz]] worked there as a journalist and illustrator for 30 years.\n\nThe 1998 circulation of the paper was 262,000 copies.<ref name=\"KiddReynolds2014\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.leprogres.fr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Progres}}\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n[[Category:Media in Lyon]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1859]]\n[[Category:1859 establishments in France]]\n\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                = Le Progr\u00e8s\n| image               = Le Progr\u00e8s newspaper nameplate.jpg\n| caption             = \n| type                = [[Daily newspaper]]\n| format              = [[Broadsheet]]\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|1859}} \n| ceased publication  = \n| price               = \n| owners              = L'est R\u00e9publicain\n| political position  = \n| publisher           = \n| editor              = \n| language       = [[French language|French]]\n| circulation         = \n| headquarters        = [[Lyon]]\n| ISSN                = \n| website             = [http://www.leprogres.fr ''Le Progr\u00e8s'']\n}}\n\n'''''Le Progr\u00e8s''''' is a regional daily newspaper which is based in [[Lyon]], [[Rh\u00f4ne (department)|Rh\u00f4ne]].<ref name=\"KiddReynolds2014\">{{cite book|author1=William Kidd|author2=Sian Reynolds|title=Contemporary French Cultural Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=45h9AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA235|accessdate=22 November 2014|date=1 May 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-4441-6556-2|page=235}}</ref>\n\n''Le Progr\u00e8s'' reports primarily on local news in the [[Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]] region. The paper has its headquarters in Lyon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Newspapers: First in a Series on the French Media|url=http://www.wikileaks.ch/cable/2006/11/06PARIS7251.html|work=Wikileaks|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=6 November 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207141142/http://www.wikileaks.ch/cable/2006/11/06PARIS7251.html|archivedate=7 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The print works is in [[Chassieu]], near Lyon. The former headquarters was located in the [[Rue de la R\u00e9publique]], in the building that is currently occupied by [[Fnac]]. [[Ren\u00e9 Diaz]] worked there as a journalist and illustrator for 30 years.\n\nThe 1998 circulation of the paper was 262,000 copies.<ref name=\"KiddReynolds2014\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.leprogres.fr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Progres}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in France]]\n[[Category:Media in Lyon]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1859]]\n[[Category:1859 establishments in France]]\n\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Progr%C3%A8s"}
{"title_page": "\u00c1lvaro Novo", "text_new": "{{spanish name 2|Novo|Ram\u00edrez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = \u00c1lvaro Novo\n| image = \n| caption = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> \n| fullname = \u00c1lvaro Novo Ram\u00edrez\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|5|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.84}} \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Don Bosco\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| years1 = 1996\u20131998 | clubs1 = [[RCD Carabanchel|Carabanchel]] | caps1 = 37 | goals1 = 10\n| years2 = 1998\u20132000 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] | caps2 = 53 | goals2 = 9\n| years3 = 2000\u20132003 | clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps3 = 101 | goals3 = 7\n| years4 = 2003\u20132005 | clubs4 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] | caps4 = 37 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2005\u20132008 | clubs5 = [[Real Sociedad]] | caps5 = 53 | goals5 = 3\n| totalcaps = 281 | totalgoals = 30\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''\u00c1lvaro Novo Ram\u00edrez''' (born 16 May 1978) is a Spanish former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfielder#Wide midfielder|right midfielder]].\n\nOver eight seasons, he amassed [[La Liga]] totals of 183 matches and 11 goals with [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]], [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] and [[Real Sociedad]].\n\n==Club career==\nNovo was born in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia]]. After finishing his football development at local [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]] he started as a senior at lowly [[RCD Carabanchel]] in [[Community of Madrid|Madrid]], helping the club to its only two [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third division]] years, after which he left in 1998.\n\nNovo then moved to [[RCD Mallorca]], first playing with [[RCD Mallorca B|the reserves]], competing [[1998\u201399 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|one season]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second level]] and being relegated. He made his debut for the main squad in the year 2000, then became an undisputed starter for the [[Balearic Islands]] side, partnering Serb [[Jovan Stankovi\u0107]] in the wings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rcdm.es/jugadores-de-ayer-y-de-hoy-alvaro-novo/|title=Jugadores de ayer y de hoy: \u00c1lvaro Novo|trans-title=Players from yesterday and today: \u00c1lvaro Novo|publisher=RCDM|last=Leal|first=Tolo|language=Spanish|date=24 November 2011|accessdate=18 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter a third place in [[La Liga]] in the [[2000\u201301 La Liga|2000\u201301 campaign]], with the subsequent [[2001\u201302 UEFA Champions League|qualification]] to the [[UEFA Champions League]], and the [[Copa del Rey]] conquest in [[2002\u201303 Copa del Rey|2003]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/06/29/deportes/1056837603_850215.html|title=Eto'o pone Mallorca a brindar|trans-title=Eto'o has Mallorca toasting|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|last=Miguelez|first=Jos\u00e9|language=Spanish|date=29 June 2003|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> Novo left for [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], rejoining former Mallorca coach [[Gregorio Manzano]] whom asked for his signing repeatedly. After the manager was replaced for [[2004\u201305 La Liga|2004\u201305]], he disappeared from the team's lineups (only five matches).<ref name=MD>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/20070809/alvaro-novo-por-mucho-que-trabaje-no-creo-que-sirva-si-ya-han-decidido-no-contar-conmigo_53383489485.html|title=\u00c1lvaro Novo: \"Por mucho que trabaje, no creo que sirva si ya han decidido no contar conmigo\"|trans-title=\u00c1lvaro Novo: \"No matter how hard I work, I don't think it will do any good if they have decided to deem me surplus\"|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=Spanish|date=9 August 2007|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2005, Novo signed with [[Real Sociedad]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2005/09/01/mas_futbol/1125556060_850215.html|title=\u00c1lvaro Novo fue el \u00fanico fichaje de \u00faltima hora|trans-title=\u00c1lvaro Novo was the only last-minute signing|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|last=S\u00e1nchez|first=Ram\u00f3n|language=Spanish|date=1 September 2005|accessdate=18 February 2014}}</ref> Again, a coaching change \u2013 [[Jos\u00e9 Mari Bakero]] was fired \u2013 made him go from an important attacking unit to a third-string squad member,<ref name=MD/> the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque]] could not release him due to his high wages and the player also refused to go on loan to neighbours [[SD Eibar]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.noticiasdegipuzkoa.com/ediciones/2008/01/30/deportes/futbol/d30fut48.908360.php|title=Novo dice \"no\" a la cesi\u00f3n al Eibar|trans-title=Novo says \"no\" to Eibar loan|newspaper=Noticias de Gipuzkoa|language=Spanish|date=30 January 2008|accessdate=16 December 2009}}</ref> his contract expired in June 2008, and he was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2018/04/11/real-sociedad/902694-otros-10-que-han-vestido-la-elastica-de-la-real-ademas-de-xabi-prieto.html|title=Otros \"10\" que han vestido la el\u00e1stica de la Real adem\u00e1s de Xabi Prieto|trans-title=Other \"10\" who have donned Real's jersey besides Xabi Prieto|publisher=[[Vavel]]|last=S\u00e1enz San Juan|first=Pablo|language=Spanish|date=11 April 2018|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|129}}\n*{{Soccerway|alvaro-novo-ramirez/3235}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Novo, Alvaro}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from C\u00f3rdoba, Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Andalusian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca B players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Sociedad footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name 2|Novo|Ram\u00edrez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = \u00c1lvaro Novo\n| image = \n| caption = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> \n| fullname = \u00c1lvaro Novo Ram\u00edrez\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|5|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[Spain]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.84}} \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Don Bosco\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| years1 = 1996\u20131998 | clubs1 = [[RCD Carabanchel|Carabanchel]] | caps1 = 37 | goals1 = 10\n| years2 = 1998\u20132000 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] | caps2 = 53 | goals2 = 9\n| years3 = 2000\u20132003 | clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps3 = 101 | goals3 = 7\n| years4 = 2003\u20132005 | clubs4 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] | caps4 = 37 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2005\u20132008 | clubs5 = [[Real Sociedad]] | caps5 = 53 | goals5 = 3\n| totalcaps = 281 | totalgoals = 30\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''\u00c1lvaro Novo Ram\u00edrez''' (born 16 May 1978) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfielder#Wide midfielder|right midfielder]].\n\nOver eight seasons, he amassed [[La Liga]] totals of 183 matches and 11 goals with [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]], [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] and [[Real Sociedad]].\n\n==Football career==\nNovo was born in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia]]. After finishing his football development at local [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]] he started as a senior at lowly [[RCD Carabanchel]] in [[Community of Madrid|Madrid]], helping the club to its only two [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third division]] years, after which he left in 1998.\n\nNovo then moved to [[RCD Mallorca]], first playing with [[RCD Mallorca B|the reserves]], competing [[1998\u201399 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|one season]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second level]] and being relegated. He made his debut for the main squad in the year 2000, then became an undisputed starter for the [[Balearic Islands]] side, partnering Serb [[Jovan Stankovi\u0107]] in the wings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rcdm.es/jugadores-de-ayer-y-de-hoy-alvaro-novo/|title=Jugadores de ayer y de hoy: \u00c1lvaro Novo|trans-title=Players from yesterday and today: \u00c1lvaro Novo|publisher=RCDM|last=Leal|first=Tolo|language=Spanish|date=24 November 2011|accessdate=18 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter a third place in [[La Liga]] in the [[2000\u201301 La Liga|2000\u201301 campaign]], with the subsequent [[2001\u201302 UEFA Champions League|qualification]] to the [[UEFA Champions League]], and the [[Copa del Rey]] conquest in [[2002\u201303 Copa del Rey|2003]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/06/29/deportes/1056837603_850215.html|title=Eto'o pone Mallorca a brindar|trans-title=Eto'o has Mallorca toasting|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|last=Miguelez|first=Jos\u00e9|language=Spanish|date=29 June 2003|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> Novo left for [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], rejoining former Mallorca coach [[Gregorio Manzano]] whom asked for his signing repeatedly. After the manager was replaced for [[2004\u201305 La Liga|2004\u201305]], he disappeared from the team's lineups (only five matches).<ref name=MD>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/20070809/alvaro-novo-por-mucho-que-trabaje-no-creo-que-sirva-si-ya-han-decidido-no-contar-conmigo_53383489485.html|title=\u00c1lvaro Novo: \"Por mucho que trabaje, no creo que sirva si ya han decidido no contar conmigo\"|trans-title=\u00c1lvaro Novo: \"No matter how hard I work, I don't think it will do any good if they have decided to deem me surplus\"|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=Spanish|date=9 August 2007|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2005, Novo signed with [[Real Sociedad]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2005/09/01/mas_futbol/1125556060_850215.html|title=\u00c1lvaro Novo fue el \u00fanico fichaje de \u00faltima hora|trans-title=\u00c1lvaro Novo was the only last-minute signing|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|last=S\u00e1nchez|first=Ram\u00f3n|language=Spanish|date=1 September 2005|accessdate=18 February 2014}}</ref> Again, a coaching change \u2013 [[Jos\u00e9 Mari Bakero]] was fired \u2013 made him go from an important attacking unit to a third-string squad member,<ref name=MD/> the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque]] could not release him due to his high wages and the player also refused to go on loan to neighbours [[SD Eibar]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www2.noticiasdegipuzkoa.com/ediciones/2008/01/30/deportes/futbol/d30fut48.908360.php|title=Novo dice \"no\" a la cesi\u00f3n al Eibar|trans-title=Novo says \"no\" to Eibar loan|newspaper=Noticias de Gipuzkoa|language=Spanish|date=30 January 2008|accessdate=16 December 2009}}</ref> his contract expired in June 2008, and he was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2018/04/11/real-sociedad/902694-otros-10-que-han-vestido-la-elastica-de-la-real-ademas-de-xabi-prieto.html|title=Otros \"10\" que han vestido la el\u00e1stica de la Real adem\u00e1s de Xabi Prieto|trans-title=Other \"10\" who have donned Real's jersey besides Xabi Prieto|publisher=[[Vavel]]|last=S\u00e1enz San Juan|first=Pablo|language=Spanish|date=11 April 2018|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|129}}\n*{{Soccerway|alvaro-novo-ramirez/3235}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Novo, Alvaro}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from C\u00f3rdoba, Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Andalusian footba