{"title_page": "Presse quotidienne nationale fran\u00e7aise", "text_new": "'''Presse quotidienne nationale fran\u00e7aise''' is a group of eighteen paid-for [[France|French]] [[daily newspaper]]s, of which six have circulations in excess of {{formatnum:100000}},<ref name=\"ojdpayant\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ojd.com/Chiffres/La-Presse/La-Presse-Payante/Presse-Quotidienne-Nationale|title=CLASSEMENT PRESSE QUOTIDIENNE NATIONALE 2013\u20132014|work=[[OJD France]]|language=fr|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref> and four [[free newspaper]]s, which have a much larger circulation: not only is the paid-for press more expensive, but there are fewer outlets from which to buy newspapers. In recent years many [[kiosk|newsstand]]s and [[newsagent]]s in Paris that sold newspapers have closed, and customers would need to travel far to get some titles.\n\n== Paid-for ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n! Name\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Founded\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Founder\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Replaced/merged\n! Group\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Major shareholders\n! Circulation (2013)<ref name=\"ojdpayant\"/>\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Remarks\n|-----\n| ''[[Le Parisien|Le Parisien / Aujourd'hui en France]]''\n| 22 August 1944\n| [[\u00c9milien Amaury]]\n| ''Le Parisien Lib\u00e9r\u00e9''\n| [[Groupe Amaury]]\n|\n| {{nts|411003}}\n| Quality general and popular paper. Centre-left politics. Circulation figures for ''Le Parisien'' and '''Aujourd'hui en France'' are combined here.\n|-----\n| ''[[Le Figaro]]''\n| Weekly: 15 January 1826<br>Daily: 1866\n| [[\u00c9tienne Arago]] and [[Maurice Alhoy]]\n| ''[[L'Aurore]]''\n| [[Socpresse]]\n| [[Groupe Industriel Marcel Dassault]] ([[Serge Dassault]])\n| {{nts|317225}}\n| General newspaper, right-wing politics.\n|-----\n| ''[[Le Monde]]''\n| 18 December 1944\n| [[Hubert Beuve-M\u00e9ry]]\n| ''[[Le Temps (1861-1942)|Le Temps]]''\n| [[Groupe Le Monde]]\n| [[Pierre Berg\u00e9]], [[Matthieu Pigasse]], [[Xavier Niel]]\n| {{nts|275310}}\n| Known as the \"[[journal of reference]]\". Politically independent, it often leans to centre-left views. ''Le Monde'' is the only [[evening newspaper]] in this list.\n|-----\n| ''[[L'\u00c9quipe]]'' (general edition)\n| 28 February 1946\n| [[Jacques Goddet]]\n| ''[[L'Auto]]''\n| [[Groupe Amaury]]\n|\n| {{nts|243580}}\n| Sports newspaper\n|-----\n| ''[[Les \u00c9chos (France)|Les \u00c9chos]]''\n| Monthly: 1908<br/>Daily: 1928\n| [[\u00c9mile Servan-Schreiber]]\n| ''Les \u00c9chos de l\u2019Exportation''\n| [[DI Group]]\n| [[LVMH]] ([[Bernard Arnault]])\n| {{nts|123636}}\n| Primarily financial. Takes a liberal-conservative editorial stance, leaning to the right.\n|-----\n| ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]''\n| 22 May 1973\n|  [[Jean-Paul Sartre]] and [[Serge July]]\n|\n| SARL Lib\u00e9ration\n| [[Patrick Drahi]] and [[Bruno Ledoux]]\n| {{nts|101616}}\n| Left-wing newspaper, aligned with the [[Parti socialiste (France)|Parti socialiste]].\n|-----\n| ''[[La Croix]]''\n| 1883\n| [[Assumptionist]]\n|\n| [[Groupe Bayard|Bayard Presse]]\n|\n| {{nts|94673}}\n| Roman-Catholic newspaper and centre-right conservative.\n|-----\n| ''[[Le Petit Quotidien]]''\n| 1998\n| Play Bac Presse\n|\n| Play Bac Presse\n|\n| {{nts|53807}}\n| For 6- to 10-year-olds.\n|-----\n| ''[[Mon quotidien]]''\n| 1995\n| Play Bac Presse\n|\n| Play Bac Presse\n|\n| {{nts|47358}}\n| For 10- to 14-year-olds.\n|-----\n| ''[[Paris Turf]]''\n| 1946\n|\n|\n| [[Turf \u00c9ditions]]\n|\n| {{nts|41393}}\n| Horse racing.\n|-----\n| ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]''\n| 18 April 1904\n| [[Jean Jaur\u00e8s]]\n|\n| Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 nouvelle du journal l'Humanit\u00e9\n|\n| {{nts|40562}}\n| Organ of the [[French Communist Party]] from 1920 to 1994; it remains close but has flirted with other left-wing bodies.\n|-----\n| ''[[Paris Courses]]''\n| 1994\n| Jean Claude Seroul\n|\n| [[Turf \u00c9ditions]]\n|\n| {{nts|20653}}\n| Horse racing.\n|-----\n| ''[[International New York Times]]''\n| 1887\n| [[James Gordon Bennett, Jr.]]\n| ''New York Herald Tribune''\n| [[New York Times Company]]\n|\n| {{nts|17167}}\n| English language newspaper.\n|-----\n| ''[[Tierc\u00e9 Magazine]]''\n| 1978\n| Jean Claude Seroul\n|\n| [[Turf \u00c9ditions]]\n|\n| {{nts|13952}}\n| Horse racing.\n|-----\n| ''[[Week End]]''\n| 1962\n| Leo Zitrone\n|\n| [[Turf \u00c9ditions]]\n|\n| {{nts|13859}}\n|\n|-----\n| ''[[La Gazette des Courses]]''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| {{nts|13847}}\n| Horse racing.\n|-----\n| ''[[Bilto]]''\n| 1985\n| Les Editions de la Bulle\n|\n| [[Turf \u00c9ditions]]\n|\n| {{nts|10405}}\n|\n|-----\n|}\n\n== Free ==\n[[Free newspaper]]s are distributed from [[kiosk|newsstand]]s and traditional [[newsagent's shop]]s at the entrances of [[metro station]]s and other public places.\n\n=== Morning ===\n* ''[[20 minutes (France)|20 minutes]]'': [[Schibsted]], a Norwegian group, launched this in France at the start of 2002. It has a circulation of {{formatnum:870000}} in France (over 8 editions) of which {{formatnum:510000}} is in Paris. With 2,160 million readers, ''20 Minutes'' is the largest general-readership newspaper in France.\n* ''[[Metronews]]'': Circulation of over {{formatnum:800000}}.\n* ''[[Direct Matin]]'': Published by a partnership of [[Bollor\u00e9]] and [[Le Monde]]. It produces its own content, and also republishes articles from ''Le Monde'' and [[Courrier international]].\n\n=== Evening ===\n* ''[[Direct Soir]]'': Published by [[Bollor\u00e9]] between 2006 and 2010. The group also publish the morning free newspaper''[[MatinPlus]]'' in partnership with the press group [[La Vie-Le Monde]].\n\n==21st century==\n*''[[Les \u00c9chos (France)|Les \u00c9chos]]'' Bought by [[LVMH]] in the fourth quarter of 2007.\n* ''[[Le Monde]]'' Management struggles in 2007 and 2008. [[Groupe Le Monde]] was replaced in 2010 by financiers [[Xavier Niel]], [[Pierre Berg\u00e9]] and [[Matthieu Pigasse]].\n* ''[[Le Figaro]]'': [[Socpresse]], publishers of ''Le Figaro'', sold this in 2004 to [[Serge Dassault]].\n* ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'': [[\u00c9douard de Rothschild]] pushed money into the title in 2005 when it found itself in financial difficulty. In 2006, [[Serge July]] (one of the founders of ''Lib\u00e9ration'' with [[Jean-Paul Sartre]]), managing editor, was forced to resign. He was replaced by [[Laurent Joffrin]], late of ''Lib\u00e9ration'' and previous director of production at ''[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]'', a magazine that was relaunched in March 2011. He was himself replaced by [[Nicolas Demorand]]. Businessman [[Bruno Ledoux]] became the second-largest shareholder in 2011. A rescue plan was launched in 2014 by Ledoux and [[Patrick Drahi]], parting company with Rothschild; Joffrin resumed the leadership.\n* ''[[France-Soir]]'' : Bought by Egyptian businessman [[Raymond Lakah]]. After another financial crisis, on 12 April 2006, it was relaunched by journalist [[Olivier Rey (journalist)|Olivier Rey]] and businessman [[Jean-Pierre Brunois]]. It was re-relaunched in 2009 by [[Alexander Pougatchev]], who closed it down in 2012.\n* ''[[La Tribune]]'' was relaunched by [[Alain Weill]] in 2007, who sold 80% to the managing director [[Val\u00e9rie Decamp]].<ref>{{cite news|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last=Reitzaum|first2=Olivia|last2=Derreumaux|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/medias/2011/12/20/04002-20111220ARTFIG00322-alain-weill-invite-du-buzz-media-orange-le-figaro.php|title=NextRadio TV doit cro\u00eetre face aux cha\u00eenes historiques|language=fr|trans-title=NextRadio TV breaks its historical chains|work=[[Le Figaro]]|date=21 December 2011|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.20minutes.fr/medias/405858-Media-Alain-Weill-cede-80-de-La-Tribune.php|title=Alain Weill c\u00e8de 80% de \"La Tribune\"|work=[[20 minutes (France)|20 Minutes]]|date=20 May 2010|accessdate=8 January 2015|language=fr}}</ref> In 2012 the newspaper later sacked him and changed from a daily to weekly format.\n* In May 2013, the weekday liberal-leaning ''[[L'Opinion]]'' was launched by [[Nicolas Beytout]].\n\nThe storm of new free titles, together with the expansion of Internet use and the closure of so many points of sale, a turndown in advertising revenue after the [[World financial crisis of 2007]], the\nL'irruption des gratuits, l'expansion d'Internet, la fermeture de nombreux points de vente, la baisse des revenus publicitaires \u00e0 la suite de la [[crise financi\u00e8re mondiale d\u00e9butant en 2007|crise \u00e9conomique de la fin des ann\u00e9es 2000]], the high cost of printing and other phenomena significantly affected the print media, especially dailies, which underwent a severe crisis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lemonde.fr/actualite-medias/article/2006/08/31/presse-quotidienne-nationale-les-raisons-d-une-crise-tres-francaise_808241_3236.html|first=Pascale|last=Santi|title=Presse quotidienne nationale : les raisons d'une crise tr\u00e8s fran\u00e7aise|date=31 August 2008|language=fr|work=[[Le Monde]]|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latribune.fr/technos-medias/medias/20120130trib000681231/la-fin-d-un-quotidien-national-symptome-d-une-presse-malade.html|first1=Sandrine|last1=Bajos|first2=Sandrine|last2=Cassini|title=La fin d'un quotidien national, sympt\u00f4me d'une presse malade|date=30 January 2012|language=fr|work=[[La Tribune]]|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telerama.fr/medias/qu-arrive-t-il-a-la-presse-ecrite,91776.php|first1=Emmanuelle|last1=Anizon|first2=Richard|last2=S\u00e9n\u00e9joux|first3=Olivier|last3=Tesquet|title=Qu'arrive-t-il \u00e0 la presse \u00e9crite? L'ab\u00e9c\u00e9daire de la crise|language=fr|date=12 January 2013|work=[[T\u00e9l\u00e9rama]]|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[French newspapers]]\n* [[Online newspaper]]\n* [[Presse quotidienne r\u00e9gionale fran\u00e7aise]], the equivalent organisation for the regional press\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Presse quotidienne nationale francaise}}\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n[[Category:Lists of newspapers]]\n[[Category:Lists of French media]]\n", "text_old": "'''Presse quotidienne nationale fran\u00e7aise''' is a group of eighteen paid-for [[France|French]] [[daily newspaper]]s, of which six have circulations in excess of {{formatnum:100000}},<ref name=\"ojdpayant\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ojd.com/Chiffres/La-Presse/La-Presse-Payante/Presse-Quotidienne-Nationale|title=CLASSEMENT PRESSE QUOTIDIENNE NATIONALE 2013\u20132014|work=[[OJD France]]|language=fr|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref> and four [[free newspaper]]s, which have a much larger circulation: not only is the paid-for press more expensive, but there are fewer outlets from which to buy newspapers. In recent years many [[kiosk|newsstand]]s and [[newsagent]]s in Paris that sold newspapers have closed, and customers would need to travel far to get some titles.\n\n== Paid-for ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n! Name\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Founded\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Founder\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Replaced/merged\n! Group\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Major shareholders\n! Circulation (2013)<ref name=\"ojdpayant\"/>\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Remarks\n|-----\n| ''[[Le Parisien|Le Parisien / Aujourd'hui en France]]''\n| 22 August 1944\n| [[\u00c9milien Amaury]]\n| ''Le Parisien Lib\u00e9r\u00e9''\n| [[Groupe Amaury]]\n|\n| {{nts|411003}}\n| Quality general and popular paper. Centre-left politics. Circulation figures for ''Le Parisien'' and '''Aujourd'hui en France'' are combined here.\n|-----\n| ''[[Le Figaro]]''\n| Weekly: 15 January 1826<br>Daily: 1866\n| [[\u00c9tienne Arago]] and [[Maurice Alhoy]]\n| ''[[L'Aurore]]''\n| [[Socpresse]]\n| [[Groupe Industriel Marcel Dassault]] ([[Serge Dassault]])\n| {{nts|317225}}\n| General newspaper, right-wing politics.\n|-----\n| ''[[Le Monde]]''\n| 18 December 1944\n| [[Hubert Beuve-M\u00e9ry]]\n| ''[[Le Temps (1861-1942)|Le Temps]]''\n| [[Groupe Le Monde]]\n| [[Pier