garo'', sold this in 2004 to [[Serge Dassault]].\n* ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'': [[\u00c9douard de Rothschild]] pushed money into the title in 2005 when it found itself in financial difficulty. In 2006, [[Serge July]] (one of the founders of ''Lib\u00e9ration'' with [[Jean-Paul Sartre]]), managing editor, was forced to resign. He was replaced by [[Laurent Joffrin]], late of ''Lib\u00e9ration'' and previous director of production at ''[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]'', a magazine that was relaunched in March 2011. He was himself replaced by [[Nicolas Demorand]]. Businessman [[Bruno Ledoux]] became the second-largest shareholder in 2011. A rescue plan was launched in 2014 by Ledoux and [[Patrick Drahi]], parting company with Rothschild; Joffrin resumed the leadership.\n* ''[[France-Soir]]'' : Bought by Egyptian businessman [[Raymond Lakah]]. After another financial crisis, on 12 April 2006, it was relaunched by journalist [[Olivier Rey (journalist)|Olivier Rey]] and businessman [[Jean-Pierre Brunois]]. It was re-relaunched in 2009 by [[Alexander Pougatchev]], who closed it down in 2012.\n* ''[[La Tribune]]'' was relaunched by [[Alain Weill]] in 2007, who sold 80% to the managing director [[Val\u00e9rie Decamp]].<ref>{{cite news|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last=Reitzaum|first2=Olivia|last2=Derreumaux|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/medias/2011/12/20/04002-20111220ARTFIG00322-alain-weill-invite-du-buzz-media-orange-le-figaro.php|title=NextRadio TV doit cro\u00eetre face aux cha\u00eenes historiques|language=fr|trans-title=NextRadio TV breaks its historical chains|work=[[Le Figaro]]|date=21 December 2011|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.20minutes.fr/medias/405858-Media-Alain-Weill-cede-80-de-La-Tribune.php|title=Alain Weill c\u00e8de 80% de \"La Tribune\"|work=[[20 minutes (France)|20 Minutes]]|date=20 May 2010|accessdate=8 January 2015|language=fr}}</ref> In 2012 the newspaper later sacked him and changed from a daily to weekly format.\n* In May 2013, the weekday liberal-leaning ''[[L'Opinion]]'' was launched by [[Nicolas Beytout]].\n\nThe storm of new free titles, together with the expansion of Internet use and the closure of so many points of sale, a turndown in advertising revenue after the [[World financial crisis of 2007]], the\nL'irruption des gratuits, l'expansion d'Internet, la fermeture de nombreux points de vente, la baisse des revenus publicitaires \u00e0 la suite de la [[crise financi\u00e8re mondiale d\u00e9butant en 2007|crise \u00e9conomique de la fin des ann\u00e9es 2000]], the high cost of printing and other phenomena significantly affected the print media, especially dailies, which underwent a severe crisis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lemonde.fr/actualite-medias/article/2006/08/31/presse-quotidienne-nationale-les-raisons-d-une-crise-tres-francaise_808241_3236.html|first=Pascale|last=Santi|title=Presse quotidienne nationale : les raisons d'une crise tr\u00e8s fran\u00e7aise|date=31 August 2008|language=fr|work=[[Le Monde]]|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latribune.fr/technos-medias/medias/20120130trib000681231/la-fin-d-un-quotidien-national-symptome-d-une-presse-malade.html|first1=Sandrine|last1=Bajos|first2=Sandrine|last2=Cassini|title=La fin d'un quotidien national, sympt\u00f4me d'une presse malade|date=30 January 2012|language=fr|work=[[La Tribune]]|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telerama.fr/medias/qu-arrive-t-il-a-la-presse-ecrite,91776.php|first1=Emmanuelle|last1=Anizon|first2=Richard|last2=S\u00e9n\u00e9joux|first3=Olivier|last3=Tesquet|title=Qu'arrive-t-il \u00e0 la presse \u00e9crite? L'ab\u00e9c\u00e9daire de la crise|language=fr|date=12 January 2013|work=[[T\u00e9l\u00e9rama]]|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[French newspapers]]\n* [[Online newspaper]]\n* [[Presse quotidienne r\u00e9gionale fran\u00e7aise]], the equivalent organisation for the regional press\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Presse quotidienne nationale francaise}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in France]]\n[[Category:Lists of newspapers]]\n[[Category:Lists of French media]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presse_quotidienne_nationale_fran%C3%A7aise"}
{"title_page": "ENASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series", "text_new": "{{short description|Series of iRacing events}}\n{{Lowercase title}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series''' is a series of [[iRacing]] events that were organized for [[NASCAR]] drivers to compete in after its 2020 seasons were put on hold due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Joseph |last=Srigley |url=https://tobychristie.com/2020/03/17/nascar-iracing-expand-partnership-to-include-enascar-iracing-pro-invitational-series/ |title=NASCAR, iRacing Expand Partnership to Include eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series |website=TobyChristie.com |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Drivers from all of NASCAR's series competed in races each weekend on virtual versions of the racetracks the [[NASCAR Cup Series]] would have raced at that weekend had the real races not been postponed. The series began at March 21 with a race at the virtual [[Homestead-Miami Speedway]]. \n\nOriginally supposed to be a one-time event, it quickly became a weekly series, and later included multiple divisions within the series.\n==Races==\n===Dixie Vodka 150===\n====Summary====\nThis was the first race of the series. [[Garrett Smithley]] won the pole and was passed by [[William Byron (racing driver)|William Byron]] on the first lap, who would go on to lead the most laps in the race. [[Denny Hamlin]] passed then-leader [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] in a photo finish on the final lap to win.\n\n====Results====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:98%\n|-\n! Pos\n! {{Tooltip|No|Car Number}}\n! Driver\n! Manufacturer\n|-\n|1 || 11 || [[Denny Hamlin]] || Toyota \n|-\n|2 || 8 || [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] || Chevrolet  \n|-\n|3 || 66 || [[Timmy Hill]] || Toyota\n|-\n|4 || 98 || [[Chase Briscoe]] || Ford\n|-\n|5 || 51 || [[Garrett Smithley]] || Chevrolet\n|-\n|6 || 88 || [[Alex Bowman]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|7 || 43 || [[Bubba Wallace]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|8 || 37 || [[Ryan Preece]] || Chevrolet\n|-\n|9 || 45 || [[Ty Majeski]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|10 || 20 || [[Erik Jones]] || Toyota\n|}\n\n===O'Reilly Auto Parts 125===\n====Qualifying race====\nThe qualifying race was held earlier on Sunday, March 29, before the main event. The drivers that advanced to the main event were [[Alex Labb\u00e9]], [[Anthony Alfredo]], [[Ty Majeski]], and [[Rub\u00e9n Garc\u00eda Jr. (racing driver)|Rub\u00e9n Garc\u00eda Jr.]], who finished first through fourth, respectively.\n\n====Top ten finishers====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:98%\n|-\n! Pos\n! {{Tooltip|No|Car Number}}\n! Driver\n! Manufacturer\n|-\n|1 || 90 || [[Alex Labb\u00e9]] || Chevrolet\n|-\n|2 || 33 || [[Anthony Alfredo]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|3 || 45 || [[Ty Majeski]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|4 || 27 || [[Rub\u00e9n Garc\u00eda Jr. (racing driver)|Rub\u00e9n Garc\u00eda Jr.]] || Ford \n|-\n|5 || 08 || [[Jeb Burton]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|6 || 5 || [[Derek Kraus]] || Toyota \n|-\n|7 || 15 || [[Brennan Poole]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|8 || 29 || [[Kaz Grala]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|9 || 52 || [[Stewart Friesen]] || Toyota \n|-\n|10 || 80 || [[Joe Graf Jr.]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|}\n\n====Main event====\n[[Timmy Hill]] won the race after executing a late bump-and-run maneuver on then-leader [[William Byron (racing driver)|William Byron]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/29/timmy-hill-wins-enascar-iracing-race-texas-results |title=Hill bumps past Byron, holds on late to win Pro Invitational race at Texas |website=NASCAR.com |publisher=NASCAR Digital Media, LLC |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Top ten finishers====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:98%\n|-\n! Pos\n! {{Tooltip|No|Car Number}}\n! Driver\n! Manufacturer\n|-\n|1 || 66 || [[Timmy Hill]] || Toyota \n|-\n|2 || 37 || [[Ryan Preece]] || Chevrolet  \n|-\n|3 || 51 || [[Garrett Smithley]] || Chevrolet \n|-\n|4 || 89 || [[Landon Cassill]]