locked into the main event at Texas, as [[Joey Gase]], [[Brennan Poole]], and [[J. J. Yeley]] were placed in the qualifying race and had to attempt to race their way in.<ref>{{cite web |first=Alexandra |last=Andrejev |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/nascar-auto-racing/article241775136.html |title=Not everyone is happy about NASCAR\u2019s new iRacing format. Some Cup drivers are left out |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |date=April 4, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nIt was announced that [[Fox NASCAR]], which normally carries this part of the NASCAR's racing season, would broadcast all iRacing Pro Invitational Series events,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/presspass/latest-news/2020/03/24/fox-sports-air-complete-enascar-iracing-pro-invitational-series |title=FOX Sports to Air Complete eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series |website=[[Fox Sports]] |date=March 24, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> which fall in a portion of the timeslots where the actual races would have been at. Fox's booth announcers [[Mike Joy]] and [[Jeff Gordon]] broadcast from Fox NASCAR's studio in Charlotte<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Weaver |url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a32037977/behind-the-scenes-of-iracing-on-fox/ |title=Behind the Scenes of iRacing on FOX\n|website=Autoweek |publisher=Hearst Digital Media |date=April 3, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> with other FOX NASCAR personalities serving in various roles on the broadcasts. \n\nLower-division races were not televised on FOX.\n\n===Television viewership===\n903,000 viewers watched the first race at Homestead, while 1,339,000 watched the second race at Texas. These races became the most-watched eSports broadcasts ever.<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Weaver |url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a31996587/texas-enascar-iracing-event-breaks-tv-record-for-esports-broadcast/ |title=Texas eNASCAR iRacing Event Breaks TV Record for Esports Broadcast |website=Autoweek |publisher=Hearst Digital Media |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NASCAR}}\n\n[[Category:Esports competitions in the United States]]\n[[Category:2020 establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Series of iRacing events}}\n{{Lowercase title}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series''' is a series of [[iRacing]] events that were organized for [[NASCAR]] drivers to compete in after its 2020 seasons were put on hold due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Joseph |last=Srigley |url=https://tobychristie.com/2020/03/17/nascar-iracing-expand-partnership-to-include-enascar-iracing-pro-invitational-series/ |title=NASCAR, iRacing Expand Partnership to Include eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series |website=TobyChristie.com |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Drivers from all of NASCAR's series competed in races each weekend on virtual versions of the racetracks the [[NASCAR Cup Series]] would have raced at that weekend had the real races not been postponed. The series began at March 21 with a race at the virtual [[Homestead-Miami Speedway]]. \n\nOriginally supposed to be a one-time event, it quickly became a weekly series, and later included multiple divisions within the series.\n==Races==\n===Dixie Vodka 150===\n====Summary====\nThis was the first race of the series. [[Garrett Smithley]] won the pole and was passed by [[William Byron (racing driver)|William Byron]] on the first lap, who would go on to lead the most laps in the race. [[Denny Hamlin]] passed then-leader [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] in a photo finish on the final lap to win.\n\n====Results====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:98%\n|-\n! Pos\n! {{Tooltip|No|Car Number}}\n! Driver\n! Manufacturer\n|-\n|1 || 11 || [[Denny Hamlin]] || Toyota \n|-\n|2 || 8 || [[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] || Chevrolet  \n|-\n|3 