ece]].\n====Top ten finishers====\n\n==Rule changes==\nAfter cars were allowed two resets if they became damaged during the race at Homestead, it was decreased to only one reset allowed for the Texas race.\n\nNot all Cup Series drivers were locked into the main event at Texas, as [[Joey Gase]], [[Brennan Poole]], and [[J. J. Yeley]] were placed in the qualifying race and had to attempt to race their way in.<ref>{{cite web |first=Alexandra |last=Andrejev |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/nascar-auto-racing/article241775136.html |title=Not everyone is happy about NASCAR\u2019s new iRacing format. Some Cup drivers are left out |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |date=April 4, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nIt was announced that [[Fox NASCAR]], which normally carries this part of the NASCAR's racing season, would broadcast all iRacing Pro Invitational Series events,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/presspass/latest-news/2020/03/24/fox-sports-air-complete-enascar-iracing-pro-invitational-series |title=FOX Sports to Air Complete eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series |website=[[Fox Sports]] |date=March 24, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> which fall in a portion of the timeslots where the actual races would have been at. Fox's booth announcers [[Mike Joy]] and [[Jeff Gordon]] broadcast from Fox NASCAR's studio in Charlotte<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Weaver |url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a32037977/behind-the-scenes-of-iracing-on-fox/ |title=Behind the Scenes of iRacing on FOX\n|website=Autoweek |publisher=Hearst Digital Media |date=April 3, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> with other FOX NASCAR personalities serving in various roles on the broadcasts. \n\nLower-division races were not televised on FOX.\n\n===Television viewership===\n903,000 viewers watched the first race at Homestead, while 1,339,000 watched the second race at Texas. These races became the most-watched eSports broadcasts ever.